  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices existed in ancient civilizations\n- Informal financial tracking to prevent criminal activities\n\n2. Modern Legal Framework:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive U.S. anti-money laundering legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required recording of cash transactions over $10,000\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created international standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed recommendations for global financial transparency\n\n4. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Made money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Established specific prosecution mechanisms\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced financial monitoring\n- Expanded AML provisions\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Strengthened counterterrorism financial regulations\n\n6. Global Regulatory Expansion:\n- Increased international cooperation\n- More comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Enhanced technological monitoring systems\n\nThis progression represents an evolving legal approach to preventing financial crimes.",
